    <text id="F0934T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>J. S. Myers offers support for Cameron's appointment to the cabinet of the
                    incoming administration.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Simon Cameron</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1861-01-23">January 23. 1861</date>
                        <name type="place">Franklin</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Hon. Simon Cameron<lb/> Washington City, D. C.<lb/> Dear Sir:--</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>I regret to know that some of our Republicans in Pennsylvania are opposing your
                    appointment as a member of the Cabinet of the in-coming administration.</p>

                <p>Can I do any thing to favor your appointment? If so, it would afford me pleasure
                    to serve you, and if you will indicate <hi rend="underline">the way</hi>, it
                    shall be done.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>Respectfully &amp;c</salute>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="underline">J.S. Myers</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <seg type="postscript">I hope our friends will not conceive it to be necessary
                        to abandon any of their principles in order to <orig reg="conciliate"
                            >concileate</orig> Traitors, but hold a firm hand, and at the same time
                            <orig reg="conciliate">concileate</orig> as much as may be, without a
                        sacrifice of principles or manhood.</seg>

                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
